[2] Bulgaria, OIE
Date: 19 Oct 2006
From: Mary Marshall <tropical.forestry@btinternet.com>
Source: OIE alert message [edited]
<http://www.oie.int/Messages/061019BGR.htm>

Bluetongue in Bulgaria
-------------------------
(Date of previous outbreak of bluetongue in Bulgaria reported to the OIE:
September 2002).
Information received on 19 Oct 2006 from Dr. Nikola T. Belev, Delegate of
Bulgaria to the OIE:
Report date: 19 Oct 2006.
Reason for immediate notification: reoccurrence of a listed disease or
infection in a country or zone/compartment following a report declaring the
outbreak(s) ended.
Date of 1st confirmation of the event: 11 Oct 2006.
Date of start of the event: 11 Oct 2006.
Clinical disease: no.
Nature of diagnosis: laboratory.
Location of the outbreaks: Burgas province.
Description of the affected population: goats in Brashlian, Byala voda and
Kalovo (2 outbreaks), villages and cattle in Evrenozovo, Rezovo and
Zvezdets villages.
Laboratory where diagnostic tests were performed: National reference
laboratory for bluetongue.
Diagnostic tests used: competitive ELISA.
Source of outbreaks or origin of infection: vectors.
Control measures undertaken:
- control of arthropods;
- quarantine;
- movement control inside the country;
- screening;
- zoning;
- disinfection of infected premises/establishment(s).
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[According to the above text, the Bulgarian notification refers to the
detection of sero-positive cattle and goats, but (not surprisingly,
considering past experience in Bulgaria) no clinical symptoms observed in
these species. If this is indeed the case, it would be interesting to get
data on the reason for the testing; if it was part of a wide scale
sero-surveillance, its scale, geographic distribution, species involved and
results will be helpful. Since these species are not supposed to have been
vaccinated, the establishment of the serotype involved is feasible and of
importance, requiring sero-neutralization testing. - Mod.AS]
******
[3] EU ADNS weekly report
Date: Sun 22 Oct 2006
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: EU, DG Health & Consumer Protection [edited]
<http://ec.europa.eu/food/animal/diseases/adns/table_11_2006/adns_201006_en.pdf>

EU Animal disease notification system (ADNS)
-----------------------------------------------
According to the 20 Oct 2006 update of table 11 (animal disease situation
per country and per disease), the total number of bluetongue outbreaks
reported by European Union member states during the period 1 Jan 2006 to 20
Oct 2006 was 1044. This includes 8 cases in a newly infected country,
Bulgaria, now added to the 4 northwestern European countries affected earlier.
The following (accumulated) number of outbreaks are reported from each of
the 5 affected EU countries:
Country / No outbreaks (previous week's data) / last date of confirmation
Belgium / 403 (297) / 19 Oct 2006
Bulgaria / 8 (0) / 11 Oct 2006
Germany / 365 (208) / 19 Oct 2006
France / 5 (4) / 13 Oct 2006
Netherlands / 263 (206) / 19 Oct 2006
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[329 newly confirmed BT outbreaks have been reported during the week 12-19
Oct 2006, of which 321 are in the 4 affected northwestern EU countries,
namely 106 in Belgium, 157 in Germany, 57 in the Netherlands and one in
France. This is a considerable, accelerating weekly increase. While last
week's increase was particularly underlined in Belgium, this week it is
Germany which demonstrates the most remarkable increase. It is noteworthy
that the (single) new outbreak in France appears after a rather long (since
5 Sep 2006) intermission.
The other 8 "outbreaks" were reported from Bulgaria (see previous item). -
Mod.AS]
